# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: archery-world-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:archery-world-cup/2006-archery-world-cup] The **2006 Archery World Cup** was the first edition of the international archery circuit, designed to highlight archery in some of the world's "most spectacular" locations following the success of the 2003 World Championships in New York City and the 2004 Summer Olympics.
[src:archery-world-cup/2006-archery-world-cup] The best individual and mixed performers in each discipline over the three legs then joined host representatives in qualifying for the finals.
[src:archery-world-cup/2006-archery-world-cup] The compound legs consisted of a 50m qualification round of 72 arrows, followed by the compound round at 50m on a 6-zone target face, using cumulative scoring for all individual, team and mixed competitions.
[src:archery-world-cup/2006-archery-world-cup] The top four individual performers (with no more than two from each country) proceeded to the finals.
[src:archery-world-cup/2006-archery-world-cup] The recurve legs consisted of a FITA qualification round, followed by a 72m Olympic set system .
[src:archery-world-cup/2006-archery-world-cup] The top seven individual performers (with no more than two from each country), plus one host nation representative if not already qualified, proceeded to the finals; the top mixed team performer proceeded to face the host nation at the finals, which were the same competition format as the legs.
[src:archery-world-cup/2006-archery-world-cup] The team competition was not competed at the finals.
[src:archery-world-cup/2006-archery-world-cup] Competitors' top three scores go towards qualification.
[src:archery-world-cup/2007-archery-world-cup] The **2007 Archery World Cup** was the 2nd edition of the international archery circuit, organised by the World Archery Federation.
[src:archery-world-cup/2008-archery-world-cup] The **2008 Archery World Cup** was the 3rd edition of the international archery circuit, organised by the World Archery Federation.
[src:archery-world-cup/2009-archery-world-cup] The **2009 Archery World Cup** was the 4th edition of the international archery circuit, organised by the World Archery Federation.
[src:archery-world-cup/2009-archery-world-cup] This was the first edition of the world cup where the mixed team events were contested at the final, with the top ranked mixed teams competing against a host country team in a one match final.
[src:archery-world-cup/2010-archery-world-cup] The **2010 Archery World Cup** was the 5th edition of the annual international archery circuit, organised by the World Archery Federation.
[src:archery-world-cup/2010-archery-world-cup] The top seven individual performers (with no more than two from each country,) plus one host nation representative if not already qualified, proceeded to the finals; the top mixed team performer proceeded to face the host nation at the finals, which were the same competition format as the legs.
[src:archery-world-cup/2010-archery-world-cup] The recurve legs consisted of a FITA qualification round, followed by a 72m Olympic set system.
[src:archery-world-cup/2011-archery-world-cup] The **2011 Archery World Cup** was the 6th edition of the annual international archery circuit, organised by the World Archery Federation.
[src:archery-world-cup/2012-archery-world-cup] The **2012 Archery World Cup** was the 7th edition of the annual international archery circuit, organised by the World Archery Federation.
[src:archery-world-cup/2012-archery-world-cup] As 2012 was an Olympic year, the World Cup consisted of three, not four legs.
[src:archery-world-cup/2012-archery-world-cup] In the compound discipline, Braden Gellenthien and Jamie van Natta produced the second consecutive United States clean sweep, while the United States topped the nations ranking for the third consecutive year.
[src:archery-world-cup/archery-world-cup] The **Archery World Cup** is a competition **outdoor**organized by World Archery, where the archers compete in four stages in four countries and the best eight archers of each category (from 2010, four archers during 2006–09) advance to an additional stage to contest the Archery World Cup Final.
[src:archery-world-cup/archery-world-cup] It has received plaudits for its innovative approach to the sport, raising its profile and reach.
[src:archery-world-cup/archery-world-cup] From 2013, the World Cup is broadcast live on Eurosport.
[src:archery-world-cup/archery-world-cup] It carries sponsorship from Kia and Longines, which supports the annual Longines Prize of Precision for archery, for the "best male and female athletes that master bow and arrow through concentration, balance, accuracy, and skill".
[src:archery-world-cup/archery-world-cup] The following venues have hosted stages of the World Cup Final.
[src:archery-world-cup/archery-world-cup] The Longines Prize for Precision is awarded to the male and female archers who shoot the most 10s over the course of the competition at the end of the season.
[src:archery-world-cup/archery-world-cup] It has been awarded since 2010 and is awarded to compound and recurve archers in alternate years.
[src:archery-world-cup/archery-world-cup] Winners receive a trophy, watch and cash prize of 5,000 CHF.
